he experiences, thoughts, and feelings of gay men and lesbians nationwide, especially as they coped with the anxieties of the McCarthy era. The letters reveal how gay people dealt with issues highly relevant to LGBT life today, including job discrimination, police harassment, marriage, homophobia in families, and persecution in churches and the military. Loftin shows that gay men and lesbians responded to intolerance and bigotry with resilience, creativity, and an invigorated belief in their right to live their lives as gay men and lesbians long before this was accepted and considered safe. Groundbreaking chapters address gay marriage and family life, international gay activism, and how antigay federal government policies reverberated throughout the country.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGay peoplezUnited States. 0aGays -- United States -- History -- 20th century. 0aGayszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomosexuality -- United States -- History -- 20th century. 0aHomosexualityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomosexualityzUnited States. 4aGender and Sexuality : Lesbian / Gay Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aHistory : Radical History. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438440163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438440163/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles